  "prompt": "What are some lesser-known sights to see when visiting Icheon, South Korea?",
  "response": "Icheon, South Korea, is often overshadowed by its more popular neighbors such as Seoul and Incheon, but it offers several lesser-known attractions that provide insight into its rich cultural and historical heritage. Here are some sights you might consider visiting:\n\n1. **Icheon Ceramics Village**: While Icheon is renowned for its ceramics, many visitors only experience the more mainstream fairs. To dive deeper, visit the lesser-known workshops and galleries in this village, where you can meet local artisans and even participate in pottery-making classes.\n\n2. **Seolbong Park**: While the park itself is popular, exploring its less-trafficked trails can offer a peaceful escape. The park's less popular areas provide serene spots for picnics and beautiful views of the lake and sculptures.\n\n3. **Woljeon Museum of Art Icheon**: This smaller museum may be overlooked in favor of the larger Icheon Ceramic Festival, but it houses significant contemporary art pieces and exhibitions that highlight local artists.\n\n4. **Icheon Hot Springs**: The city is known for its hot springs, some of which are less commercialized than others. Visiting a traditional jjimjilbang (Korean bathhouse) in a less touristy area can offer a more authentic experience.\n\n5. **Icheon Tomb of Seolbong**: This historical site may not be on every tourist's itinerary, but it provides a glimpse into the region's history. It\u2019s a peaceful area that tells stories of Korea's past rulers and their resting places.\n\n6. **Baeksa Village**: A bit off the beaten path, this traditional hanok village gives you a feel of Korea\u2019s past. Wandering through the village is like stepping back in time and offers great opportunities for photography.\n\n7. **Icheon Apple Theme Park**: Not your typical park, this quirky attraction celebrates the apple farming heritage of the region. It features activities related to apple cultivation and local agricultural traditions.\n\nExploring these lesser-known sights can enrich your visit to Icheon, offering a more well-rounded view of its cultural and historical significance.",
